<span style="font-family:'Courier New', Courier, monospace; letter-spacing: 2px; text-shadow: 3px 3px #a020f0, -3px -3px #32cd32;">'''Level 345'''</span>  is the 346<sup>th</sup> level of the Backrooms discovered by [[M.E.G.]] on May 18th, 2011.<ref>Recovered from fragmented M.E.G. archival logs. Exact expedition team unknown.</ref>

----

== Description ==
{{Blurimage|file=Level 345...photo.png|caption=<code>Picture 1:</code> First known image from Backrooms Level 345 on 7/10/2010.}}

<span style="font-family:'Courier New', Courier, monospace; letter-spacing: 2px; text-shadow: 3px 3px #a020f0, -3px -3px #32cd32;">'''Level 345'''</span>, also known as '''''The Dreamcore Town''''', resembles a peculiar, quiet town, perpetually stuck in a late spring afternoon. The sky is unusually clear, colored a faint cyan-green tint.  There are never any changes to the overall brightness, nor is there any real sense of time passing.

Early 2010s suburban houses flank the sides of the streets and sidewalks, with one house roughly every 0.02km. Each house has a lawn, consisting of two separate plots of well-maintained grass, measured to take up a surface area of roughly 0.15km and 0.08km, respectively. Both of these plots are separated by a clean, concrete driveway. Flanking the sides of the plots is a basic mangrove wooden fence, about 4 meters tall. The front porches of the houses lack any decorations, nor any unique paint jobs. Everything looks new, lacking any signs of damage, wear, or abandonment. Likewise, there is a complete absence of any residents or general intelligent life.

Despite looking peaceful and nostalgic, the area appears subtly unnatural.<ref>Extended habitation is not recommended.</ref>

== Exterior Environment ==
The lawns of each house throughout  <span style="font-family:'Courier New', Courier, monospace; letter-spacing: 2px; text-shadow: 3px 3px #a020f0, -3px -3px #32cd32;">'''Level 345'''</span> appear, and are, very well kept. The grass varies in color slightly from one property to another, though the pattern is suspected to appear intentional rather than natural. 

Small oak trees line the sidewalks at fixed distances, about 1/80 km apart. Cars can be seen parked in driveways, lacking any keys inside the vehicle and the respective house they are parked at. Fuel gauges consistently read half-full, with full disregard to the vehicle's type, battery life, or mechanical specifications. No successful attempts to start any of them have been recorded, let alone if the aforementioned can be started.

From a distance, <span style="font-family:'Courier New', Courier, monospace; letter-spacing: 2px; text-shadow: 3px 3px #a020f0, -3px -3px #32cd32;">'''Level 345'''</span> seems to continue indefinitely. The streets curve from time to time, at most up to a 60-degree angle. Presumed to be an anomalous property, Wanderers who walk in a straight line often return to their starting point without noticing any transition. This has been referred to as [[Phenomenon 14]].

== Structures ==
{{Blurimage|caption=<code>Picture 2:</code> Inside a house in Level 345.|file=E567645.png}}

Homes within <span style="font-family:'Courier New', Courier, monospace; letter-spacing: 2px; text-shadow: 3px 3px #a020f0, -3px -3px #32cd32;">'''Level 345'''</span> are typically unlocked.

The rooms within the houses are clean, contain very little furniture, if any, and freshly painted. The layout resembles that of a 2010s  [[The Frontrooms|Frontrooms-era]] suburban home, which often consists of an entrance hall, living room, kitchen, and bedrooms upstairs, among other layouts.

The furniture inside each house appears visibly re-arranged, though there is a total lack of any possible use. Counterintuitively, general clothing, movies, etc, can be found in their respective furnishing types. Dust is next to non-existent on most surfaces, and likewise is present on some. Air vents will very often contain heavy buildup of

dust, dirt, and mold; typically paired with a filter that is long overdue to be changed. Thus suggesting long periods of neglect.

Clocks throughout each of the houses function normally, though they do not display the same time. Some differ by only a few minutes, while others are off by several hours.

{{Blurimage|caption=<code>Picture 3:</code> A Television with blue screen.|file=Bluescrren.png}}

Other electrical systems work as expected. Stoves heat up, air conditioning cools (or warms up) the houses, and lights brighten up dark rooms. Televisions, however, display only a bright blue screen with no sound.

Mirrors and windows function without any noticeable changes. While unconfirmed, some wanderers report that, after prolonged staring, their reflections begin to move slightly slower than they do.

=== The Children's Rooms ===

{{Blurimage|file=A bed in level 345.png|caption=<code>Picture 4:</code> Children's room.}}

Most houses contain a single furnished children's bedroom, typically featuring a neatly made bed, complete with animal- or car-themed coverings, a small desk, and shelves stocked with children's literature. Toys within these rooms are consistently found in symmetrical arrangements and never appear displaced. Among such toys are trucks, toy soldiers, stuffed animals, and others.

Crayons and drawing materials are always found on desks, paired with scattered sheets of paper which occasionally feature simple sketches of houses—standard square structures with triangular roofs and a sun in the corner. Notably, the sun is positioned at the exact same angle in every drawing found, and there are never any drawings depicting rain or weather that is not sunny.

Wanderers have reported seeing faint impressions in the carpet, suggesting someone had recently been sitting cross-legged on the floor; however, these marks typically fade within minutes of discovery.

== Entities ==

{{Entity Class|Agg=3|Int=4|Dan=3|no=345-A|Hab=345}}{{Blurimage|file=Entity 345-A.png|caption=<code>Picture 5:</code> Entity 345-A captured.}}

=== '''The Threshold Figure''' ===
The Threshold Figure appears as a human-like being, and is most often seen in doorways, hallways, or rooms that are not fully empty. Sometimes, the entity will favor rooms that aren't dark nor bright, though why remains unknown. In one recorded case, the figure stood in a doorway, slightly leaning its upper body into the doorframe, with its lower portion set back likewise, hidden from view. The upper part of its body was the easiest to make out, though it still blended heavily into the room's lack of lighting. No clear features can be seen on the entity.

The entity appears to be fluid in general mass, and absorbs the light around it, which makes The Threshold Figure appear two-dimensional and without visible texture or depth. It can only be distinguished through its shape causing displacement from its surroundings in dark environments.

The head, body, and limbs are only suggested through it outline. There are no visible body details or facial features, save for two green spots that can be seen near the top of a presumed head. These reflect light to an extent, similar to cat eyes. After further study of images of the alleged entity, these are presumed to be the eyes of The Threshold Figure.

The Threshold Figure, or Entity 345-A, is usually reported in the basements of the houses, where it's believed to watch other Wanderers. The entity remains completely still while being observed, often times indistinguishable from the darkness from a careful glance. <ref>It does not change its behavior and does not interact with anything around it.</ref>

'''Notes:'''

* Entity 345-A is believed to be easier to see when there is a substantial amount of light pointed in it's general direction.
* It is not clear whether Entity 345-A is physically present or if it is something people only perceive in dark environments.
* The two green spots are the only feature that remains consistent across sightings.<ref>There is insufficient data regarding the effects of prolonged observation of Entity 345-A.</ref>

== Psychological Hazards ==
{{Blurimage|caption=<code>Picture 6:</code> A picture of Level 345 showing a phenomenon where the houses repeat.|file=LEvel 345 Phenomena.png}}

Long-term observation changes the way people think. Wanderers report feeling disconnected from their surroundings, as if the environment becomes less clear the longer they look at it.

Some notable effects are:

* It becomes harder to tell the figure apart from the shadow around it. The figure does not move, but it seems to settle into darker areas on purpose.
* Depth perception becomes unreliable. The space between the observer and the entity may seem to change for no obvious reason.
* Wanderers often feel an urge to return to the nearest exit, usually a door. There is no sound or movement that matches this feeling.
* Some anomalies have only been reported in peripheral vision:
** If a person does not look directly at the corners of a room, they may appear slightly distorted.
** The lighting seems unchanged, but the shadows grow darker over time.
** The outline of the entity is often easier to see when it is not being looked at directly.
* The figure does not show direct aggression. There have been no reports of movement, speech, or approach.
* Even so, long-term exposure causes lasting psychological stress. The environment becomes more oppressive over time, despite there being no clear reason for it. <ref>People often stop trying to leave, even though they do not know why.</ref>

== Anomalies & phenomena ==
<center>'''<u>The Nostalgia Hallucination</u>'''</center>
{{Phenomenon Class|danger=2|effectiveness=4|frequency=4}}
People who walk around this level for long periods of time, usually 6–8 hours, often report a number of psychological and auditory effects. These things happen in stages:

'''Stage I: Psychological Erosion (6–8 Hours)'''

The first signs include a slight decline in cognitive stability, such as:

* Cognitive Dissociation: a slight but ongoing change in short-term memory.
* The "False Familiarity" Effect: a phenomenon characterized by an instinctive recognition of spatial layouts in an unfamiliar location.
* Entrance Amnesia: a growing inability to remember the exact circumstances or point of entry into the level.

'''Stage II: Auditory Disturbances (24+ Hours)'''

After a full day, subjects report hearing sounds that are not real. People describe these sounds as clear and close, but they cannot be traced back to anything physical. Common reports include:

* The loud sound of a wooden door closing on an upper floor.
* The steady, hollow rolling of a small object that sounds like a toy moving across hardwood floors.
* Low-frequency humming or voices coming from nearby empty rooms.

'''Status of Verification:'''

Despite repeated acoustic monitoring and physical sweeps, there is still no evidence that these sounds come from living things or machines. They appear to be tied to the subject’s presence in the level rather than to the environment itself.

== Colonies and Outposts ==
There are no colonies in <span style="font-family:'Courier New', Courier, monospace; letter-spacing: 2px; text-shadow: 3px 3px #a020f0, -3px -3px #32cd32;">'''Level 345'''</span>, these are not feasible due to the psychological effects mentioned above.
{{Quote|I stayed longer than I should have.

At first, it felt safe and quiet, like a normal place. The houses looked fine, like people actually lived there.

I remember thinking it was not that bad, or even that I had once lived in this town.

After a while, things started to feel off.

I kept walking down the street, thinking I was making progress. I always ended up back where I started. I did not notice it at first.

I also started hearing things. A lawnmower. Kids laughing. It sounded close, but I never saw anything.

I went into one of the houses and found a small bedroom. It looked like a kid's room. There were drawings on the desk. They all looked the same.

For some reason, that made me feel uneasy.

After a while, I started to feel like I knew the place. Like I had been there before. That was when I realized something was wrong with me.

I do not remember how long I stayed.

If you are reading this, do not stay long. It gets harder to leave the longer you are here.

I am trying to leave now.|Found note from a wanderer in Level 345 Status is Unknown.|color=color:#f0f8ff; text-shadow: 0 0 4px #66ffff;}}
<div style="text-align:right;"></div>

== Entrances and Exits ==

=== Entrances ===
* You can enter <span style="font-family:'Courier New', Courier, monospace; letter-spacing: 2px; text-shadow: 3px 3px #a020f0, -3px -3px #32cd32;">'''Level 345'''</span> by:
** Staring at a town photograph for an extended period in [[Level 4]], which may cause nearby walls to shift into the architecture of this level.
** Following the sound of a distant school bell in [[Level 11]] until you find a door that should not be there.
** Noclipping through a locker that has the number 345 scratched into the metal door.

=== Exits ===
{{Blurimage|file=LEvel 345 Exit stairs.png|caption=<code>Picture 7:</code> An exit from Level 345.}}
Exits are inconsistent but possible.

* Walking into direct sunlight until a visual whiteout occurs may cause one to noclip into [[Level 89]].
* Entering a child’s closet and closing the door behind oneself may result in emergence within [[Level 320]].
* Falling asleep inside a furnished bedroom may result in awakening in [[Level 94]].
* Touching a small, round turquoise toy ball toy replica of a wireframe sphere found within the residential buildings in this level will cause an immediate transition to [[Level 346]].
* Other exits remain unknown.

== Survival Tips ==

{{M.E.G Notice|notice=
Don’t let the bedrooms "''trick you.''"
It feels so much like home that it hurts, but that’s the trap. If Wanderers start having "memories" of playing in these halls as a kid, get out. Fast. If you stay, you’ll eventually forget who you actually are.

Ignore the neighborhood '''sounds.'''
Subjects hear a lawnmower or kids laughing a few houses down. Looking for the source is not recommended. There is nobody there. People just walk until their feet bleed and end up right back where they started.|reason=Following repeated incidents on Level 345, the M.E.G. has established these guidelines to mitigate further risks.}}

